node.text: Technically, very far from oceanfront property. On July 1 the folks at @wavegarden_official open the doors at a new facility in Praia da Grama, 60 miles outside of São Paulo, Brazil. Instead of equating the new park to a Disneyland-like atmosphere, think of this newest development as part of a gated community. Literally. The pool is being touted as the centerpiece of Fazenda da Grama, which also features one of Brazil’s top 18-hole golf courses, horse riding, beach volleyball, tennis, gym, swimming and spa facilities, restaurants, a surf shop, event space, and an agroforest, all for its residents.

node.title: Brazil Has a New Wavegarden Cove Inside a Private Residential Complex

node.text:
It was not a winter for the faint of heart off the coast of Half Moon Bay, California. The Pacific Ocean lit up and the world’s best big wave surfers were there to charge. And a new contest, the @maverickssurfawards , was implemented this season to replace the one-day surf contest format. This recap features some of the best and craziest moments from an already crazy winter at Mavericks. 

Like we said, it wasn’t a winter for the faint of heart.

#surfsomething

node.title: Surfing Giant Mavericks: Was This the Best Winter in 20 Years?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The Inertia on July 20, 2021. May be an image of ocean and text that says 'THE BEST PARBOUT ABOUT SURFING IS COMPLAINING ABOUT SURFING'.

node.text:
“Sharing the frustration over a slightly too high tide ruining what appears to be the perfect oncoming set wave or swapping that annoyed, quizzical weekend look of ‘where did all of these people come from?’ with another local is the best way to cope through surfing’s valleys. To finally have the revelation that everyone despises this sport for the same reasons as you is wildly gratifying in ways that landing an aerial never will be.” ~ Jason Nauman

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The Inertia in Great Lakes. May be an image of ocean and text that says 'GREAT LAKES SURFERS COULD SOON FACE $500 FINE 'WHEN WAVES ARE 3 TO 5 FEET OR HIGHER''.

node.text:
In June, the Michigan Department of Natural Resources Director Dan Eichinger proposed banning entering the water on so-called “Red Flag” days, when waves are three to five feet or higher, and conditions are deemed “dangerous.” The proposed order, if passed, would go into effect this August.

Currently, swimmers and water sports enthusiasts are only “recommended” against entering the water on Red Flag days. The proposed order would prohibit anyone from exiting “the state-managed beaches for the purpose of entry into the water when entry is prohibited by signage and/or communication by a department employee or their designee.” The penalty for disobeying the order qualifies as a state civil infraction and carries a fine of up to $500. • 

As you can imagine, surfers, kite boarders, and other locals are not enthusiastic about this potential ban • READ THE STORY ON THE INERTIA via @sillwileo 

#surfsomething #greatlakes #news
